revision.text:
[[File:Camisa.jpg|thumb|A camisa blouse]] The '''''camisa'' blouse''' is a garment that originated in the [[Philippines]]. It is made from a cloth that has been woven using thread made from the [[pineapple]] plant. The thread is known as [[piña]] thread. Clothing and accessories, like shawls, were made out of piña. These began to be woven in the Philippines in the 16th century, and are still being made today. THE TEXTILE MUSEUM says that "The pineapple plant is not a native species to the Philippines it is thought to have been introduced by the [[Spanish people|Spanish]]". Because the cloth took a very long time to make, it was highly sought after and wearing a '''camisa blouse''' was seen as a sign of wealth.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.textilemuseum.org/totm/camisaindex.htm | title=Camisa (blouse) | accessdate=December 1, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016055635/http://www.textilemuseum.org/totm/camisaindex.htm# | archive-date=2011-10-16 | dead-url=yes | df= }}</ref>
By the 1850s, the sleeves of the carmisa blouse, which were made out of the embroidered piña thread became larger and tubular in shape.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IBdpE-aUchkC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=%22Camisa+blouse%22&source=bl&ots=vOzaFKUYlY&sig=6FCUCEhy4Z5KtqAD0UwrG6qoOzA&hl=en&ei=jVTXTp7nMoeRiQes7PzEDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22Camisa%20blouse%22&f=false | title=The Politics of Dress in Asia and the Americas | accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref>
