This is a '''List of militaries that recruit foreign applicants'''. This includes any individuals who are [[Alien (law)|aliens]] of the [[sovereign state|state]] whose [[armed forces]] they are being recruited to join by [[Military recruitment|professional recruiters]]. The foreigners need not be legal residents of that nation, but may gain legal residence status by joining the armed forces.
{{AlphanumericTOC|numbers=|}}

==A==
* {{flag|Australia}}
** [[Australian Armed Forces|Australian Defence Force]] - The ADF routinely recruits New Zealand citizens who are [[Australian permanent resident|Permanent Residents]] to serve in the military.<ref name="defencejobs.gov.au">{{cite web|url=http://www.defencejobs.gov.au/recruitment-centre/can-i-join/citizenship/|title=Do I have to be an Australian citizen to join the Australian Defence Force?|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>
** Permanent residents who can prove they have applied for citizenship. Or permanent residents who are ineligible to apply for Australian citizenship as long as they are prepared to apply for citizenship within 3 months of commencing service (or 6 months if in the ADF Reserve). If permanent residents refuse citizenship or fail in their application, their ADF service will be terminated.
** Overseas applicants with relevant military experience from allied countries who have significant military experience can apply to join the Armed Forces. A willingness to apply for citizenship is a requirement. In exceptional circumstances, if a position cannot be filled by an Australian Citizen the citizenship requirement may be waived and applications may be accepted from:<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/defence/defence-hunting-foreign-troops-with-citizenship-for-service/story-e6frg8yo-1226230857780|title = Defence hunting foreign troops with citizenship for service|last = Nicholson|first = Brendan|date = December 27, 2011|work = |access-date = July 18, 2015|via = |newspaper = [[The Australian]]}}</ref> In certain areas of the defence, especially sensitive work that involves collaboration with [[Australian Security Intelligence Organisation|ASIO]] or [[Australian Secret Intelligence Service|ASIS]], citizenship is a requirement.<ref name="defencejobs.gov.au"/>

==B==
* {{flagcountry|Bahrain}}
** The [[Bahrain Defence Force|forces in Bahrain]] are made up of Sunni foreigners, mainly Arabs and Pakistanis serving within them. This has  become a topic of debate; the majority Shia Bahrainis are not happy with foreigners in the positions of power while the native Bahrainis are barred from them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.shiapost.com/2014/03/20/hiring-of-pakistani-fighters-for-bahrain-angers-iran/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429050302/http://en.shiapost.com/2014/03/20/hiring-of-pakistani-fighters-for-bahrain-angers-iran/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2014-04-29|title=Hiring of Pakistani fighters for Bahrain angers Iran|author=shiapost|work=The Shia Post}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=Sectarian bias|date=May 2016}}</ref> 
* {{flag|Belgium}}
** [[Belgian Armed Forces]] - Any [[Citizenship of the European Union|citizen of a country of the European Union]] within the age of 18 to 34 (33 for officers) is eligible to join the forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/be/news/Belgian-army-attracts-foreigners_129809.html|title=Belgian army attracts foreigners|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.vtg.admin.ch/internet/vtg/de/home/schweizerarmee/organisation/hkaneu/milak/militaerwissenschaftliche/militaersozioligie/publikationen.parsys.93405.downloadList.55440.DownloadFile.tmp/519szvircsevrecruitmentofmilitaryprofessionalsbyeuropean2009.pdf|title = Recruitment of Military Professionals by European All-Volunteer Forces as Exemplified by Belgium, the Netherlands and Slovenia|date = |accessdate = July 18, 2015|website = |publisher = Swiss Military Academy at [[ETH Zurich]]|last = Szvircsev Tresch|first = Tibor|quote = "Thus, the armed forces of Belgium and Luxemburg also recruit other EU citizens"}}</ref><ref>https://lirias.kuleuven.be/bitstream/123456789/409847/1/Lescreve+%26+Schreurs+(2007),+Recruiting+and+retention+of+military+personnel+Belgium.pdf</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Bolivia}}
** Foreign nationals resident in Bolivia at conscription age are permitted to join the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|armed forces]], which simplifies their naturalization process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/4b7cee773c.html|title=Refworld - Bolivia: Citizenship law, including methods by which a person may obtain citizenship; whether dual citizenship is recognized|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|last=Refugees|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>

==C==
* {{flag|Canada}}
** [[Canadian Forces]] - Canadian permanent residents are allowed to serve in the Canadian Forces (CF) as long as the Chief of the Defence Staff (CDS) decides it would not prejudice the national interest. It is likely that a requirement of CF membership will be to aim to become a Canadian citizen within four years of enrollment (subject to Citizenship and Immigration Canada's (CIC) processing timeframes).  Following changes to the Citizenship Act in 2015, there is also now a fast-track citizenship scheme available to current and past CF members, as well as certain prospective members (negating the requirement to become a permanent resident first in the latter case).  
* {{flag|Cyprus}}
** [[Cypriot National Guard]] - Cyprus accepts all foreign nationals of at least partial [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] descent as volunteers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.cy/mfa/HighCom/london.nsf/All/ADCB88A968E8730D80257B79004FBDE4?OpenDocument|title=HIGH COMMISSION OF THE REPUBLIC OF CYPRUS IN LONDON - Consular Information|website=www.mfa.gov.cy|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>

==D==
* {{flag|Denmark}}
** Foreign nationals already living in Denmark or in another EU country may apply to join the Danish armed forces, providing they have lived one year in Denmark if applying within or six years if applying within an EU country. However, they must be fluent in Danish and must be able to write it as well<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.um.dk/en/travel-and-residence/defense-and-security/danish-military-service-for-foreign-nationals/|title=Danish Military Service for Foreign Nationals|work=um.dk}}</ref>

==F==
* {{flag|France}}
** [[French Foreign Legion]] - The Legion is a branch of the [[French Army]], which recruits applicants aged 18 to 39.5 from throughout the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://foreignlegion.info/joining/|title = Joining the French Foreign Legion|date = |accessdate = July 18, 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

==G==
* {{flag|Greece}}
** [[Hellenic Armed Forces]] - Ethnic Greeks accepted to the military academies for officers or non-commissioned officers of the Greek armed forces (according to the special law governing each school) or who enlist in the armed forces as volunteers (according to the law governing each branch) acquire Greek nationality automatically from the time they enter the academies or are enlisted. Knowledge of Greek language at fluent level is required.

==I==
* {{flagcountry|India}}
** [[Indian Army]] - Recruits [[Gorkha regiments (India)|Nepalese]] and Bhutanese citizens, and the refugees from [[Tibet]] who intend to permanently settle in India.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url = http://www.joinindianarmy.nic.in/writereaddata/Portal/NotificationPDF/DETAILED_NOTIFICATION_AEC_122.pdf|title = Army Education Corps|date = |accessdate = July 18, 2015|website = Join Indian Army|publisher = |last = |first = |quote = "A candidate must either be : (i) A citizen of India, or (ii) A subject of Bhutan, or (iii) A subject of Nepal, or (iv) a Tibetan refugee who came over to India before the 1st of January 1962 with the intention of permanently settling in India or (v) a person of Indian origin who has migrated from Pakistan, Burma, Sri Lanka and East African countries of Kenya, Uganda, the United Republic of Tanzania, Zambia, Malawi, Zaire and Ethiopia and Vietnam with the intention of permanently settling in India."}}</ref> Recruits of Indian origin who have migrated from Pakistan, Burma, Sri Lanka, Kenya, Thailand, Uganda, Tanzania, Zambia, Malawi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, and Vietnam with the intention of permanently settling in India may also join.<ref name=":1" /> 
* {{flagcountry|Ireland}}
** [[Irish Defence Forces]] - Nationals of the European Economic Area, which includes member states of the European Union along with Iceland, Liechtenstein and Norway, as well as foreign residents having lived in Ireland for 5 years continuously.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.military.ie/careers/faq/|title = Frequently Asked Questions|date = |accessdate = |website = Defence Forces Ireland|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Israel}}
** [[Israel Defense Forces]] - [[Israel]] recruits non-Israeli [[Jews]]—and non-Jews with at least one Jewish grandparent—through the [[Mahal (Israel)|Mahal]] and [[Garin Tzabar]] programs. They also recruit converts to Judaism.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/monkey-cage/wp/2014/07/22/foreign-fighters-for-israel/|title = Foreign Fighters’ for Israel|last = Malet|first = David|date = July 22, 2014|work = |access-date = July 18, 2015|via = |newspaper = [[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>

==L==
* {{flagcountry|Luxembourg}}
** [[Luxembourg Army]] - Any [[Citizenship of the European Union|citizen of a country of the European Union]] who has resided in Luxembourg for at least 36 months and is at least 18 years old but not yet 24 is eligible to join the army.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.wort.lu/en/luxembourg/adr-bill-proposal-luxembourg-nationality-for-foreign-army-volunteers-555dee8e0c88b46a8ce59b39|title = Luxembourg nationality for foreign army volunteers|last = |first = |date = May 21, 2015|work = |access-date = July 18, 2015|via = |newspaper = [[Luxemburger Wort]]}}</ref>

==M==
* {{flag|Monaco}}
** [[Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince]] and the [[Military of Monaco#Military and Civil Defence|Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers]] - Recruits [[Frenchmen]], as well as native [[Monegasques]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/francais/maison-souveraine/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers-de-s-a-s-le-prince.70.html |title=La Compagnie des Carabiniers de S.A.S. le Prince - Palais Princier de Monaco |publisher=Palais.mc |date= |accessdate=2013-10-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609024338/http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/francais/maison-souveraine/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers-de-s-a-s-le-prince.70.html |archivedate=2012-06-09 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pompiers.gouv.mc/321/wwwnew.nsf/1909!/x4Fr?OpenDocument&4Fr |title=Le recrutement : Principaute de Monaco |publisher=Pompiers.gouv.mc |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>

==N==
* {{flag|New Zealand}}
** Overseas: A serving member of another military can join the New Zealand Defence Force. The Requirements are to be a current or recently serving (within 6–12 months) member of the UK, Australian, US or Canadian Armed Forces, have been a citizen of either the UK, Australia, US, or Canada for a minimum period of 10 years, or have been living in NZ for a minimum period of 5 years, be eligible for release from current service within 18 months of applying, and meet current vacancy criteria at the time of application.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defencecareers.mil.nz/reenlistoverseas/overseas-applicants|title=Overseas Applicants|website=Defence Careers|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>
* {{flag|Norway}}
** [[Norwegian Armed Forces]] - By agreement between the two countries [[Icelandic nationality law|citizens of Iceland]] are accepted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stortinget.no/no/Saker-og-publikasjoner/Sporsmal/Skriftlige-sporsmal-og-svar/Skriftlig-sporsmal/?qid=50854 |title=Skriftlig spørsmål |publisher=stortinget.no |date=2011 |accessdate=2013-10-17 |language=Norwegian |trans-title=Written questions from Dagfinn Høybråten (Christian Democratic Party) to the Minister of Defence}}</ref>

==R==
* {{flagcountry|Russia}}
** The [[Russian Foreign Legion|Russian Armed Forces]] accepts foreigners of any country to their ranks. Under a plan, posted on the ministry’s web site in 2010, foreigners without [[dual citizenship]] are able to sign up for five-year contracts – and  are eligible for Russian citizenship after serving three years. According to the amended law, a citizen of any foreign country aged 18–30 with a good command of Russian and a clean record can sign an initial five-year contract to join the Army.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.themoscownews.com/news/20101125/188233351.html |title=Russia’s new Foreign Legion &#124; NEWS |publisher=The Moscow News |date=2010-11-25 |accessdate=2013-10-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717014643/http://www.themoscownews.com/news/20101125/188233351.html |archivedate=2011-07-17 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rttnews.com/1782797/russia-s-military-to-recruit-more-foreigners.aspx |title=Russia's Military To Recruit More Foreigners |publisher=Rttnews.com |date=2011-12-16 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/military_news/20101125/161492830.html |title=Russia military looks to recruit more foreigners &#124; Defense &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date=2010-11-25 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>

==S==
* {{flagcountry|Serbia}}
** [[Serbian Armed Forces]] - Serbian Armed Forces recruits citizens of former [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], [[Citizenship of the European Union|European Union member states]] and [[Post-Soviet states|former Soviet republics]]. Individuals must be 18–30 years old and with a good command of [[Serbian Language]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
* {{flagcountry|Spain}}
** [[Spanish Armed Forces]] - Spain recruits citizens of ex-Spanish colonies (except [[Puerto Rico]] and the [[Philippines]]). Citizens of [[Argentina]], [[Bolivia]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Colombia]], [[Cuba]], [[Chile]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Ecuador]], [[El Salvador]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], [[Mexico]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Panama]], [[Paraguay]], [[Peru]], [[Uruguay]] or [[Venezuela]] may enlist in the [[Spanish Legion]] (except as submarine personnel) with temporary/permanent residence or acquired Spanish citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.vtg.admin.ch/internet/vtg/de/home/schweizerarmee/organisation/hkaneu/milak/militaerwissenschaftliche/militaersozioligie/publikationen.parsys.93405.downloadList.55440.DownloadFile.tmp/519szvircsevrecruitmentofmilitaryprofessionalsbyeuropean2009.pdf|title = Recruitment of Military Professionals by European All-Volunteer Forces as Exemplified by Belgium, the Netherlands and Slovenia.|date = |accessdate = July 18, 2015|website = Swiss Military Academy at [[ETH Zurich]]|publisher = |last = Szvircsev Tresch|first = Tibor|quote = Spain even integrates Spanish-speaking South Americans into its armed forces.}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Singapore}}
** Singapore has always made use of [[Gurkha]]s to help with special military and police roles. During the colonial days, many soldiers were brought to Singapore from other British colonies. Second-generation male permanent residents are bound by [[National service in Singapore|Singapore's conscription laws]] to the same extent Singaporean citizens are, and therefore must do the standard active and reserve service in the military, police, or civil defense force.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/press_room/official_releases/ps/2011/22nov11_ps.html#.VNq-pvnF8kd|title=MINDEF - Parliamentary Statements - Written Reply by Minister for Defence Dr Ng Eng Hen to Parliamentary Question on Permanent Residents in National Service (22 Nov 11)|work=mindef.gov.sg}}</ref>

==U==
* {{flag|Ukraine}}
** It has been reported that [[Citizenship of the European Union|EU]], Georgian and [[Belarusian citizenship|Belarus]]ian citizens have been serving in the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]] since the outbreak of the [[Donbass War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.info/politics/1173085-poroshenko-legalizes-foreigners-in-ukrainian-army.html|title=Poroshenko legalizes foreigners in Ukrainian Army|language=English|date=3 November 2015}}</ref>
* {{flag|United Kingdom}} 
** [[British Armed Forces]] - The British Army has continued the historic practice of recruiting [[Gurkhas]] from [[Nepal]] to serve in special Gurkha units. The Gurkhas are selected and recruited in Nepal, and are expected to keep their Nepali citizenship throughout the length of their service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/gurkhas/27835.aspx|title=Gurkha terms and conditions of service|work=mod.uk}}</ref>
** In 1989 previous restrictions on the enlistment of Commonwealth citizens in the British Armed Forces were lifted, following recruiting difficulties amongst British citizens. Under the new provisions Commonwealth citizens were permitted to enlist directly in any one of the British services and significant numbers did so in subsequent years. From 2013, all Commonwealth citizens except for those from Cyprus, the Republic of Ireland (not a member of the commonwealth) and Malta must have resided for 5 years in the UK before being allowed to join.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ian|last=Drury |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2360771/Commonwealth-citizens-live-Britain-years-joining-Armed-Forces-ministers-try-cut-military-numbers.html |title=Commonwealth citizens will have to live in Britain for five years before joining Armed Forces as ministers try to cut military numbers &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date= 2013-07-11|accessdate=2013-10-17 |location=London}}</ref> As of the 23rd of May 2016, some of these restrictions for certain positions requiring residency in the United Kingdom have been lifted for Commonwealth citizens, due to recruiting difficulties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joining from the Commonwealth|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/join/commonwealth_joiners.aspx?t=/commonwealth|language=English}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|United States}}
** [[United States Armed Forces]] - Permanent Residence/Green Card. Many have also served in the war zones and have received US citizenship after a period of service.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2000/07/can_noncitizens_join_the_military.html|title = Can Non-Citizens Join the Military?|last = |first = |date = July 7, 2000|work = [[Slate Magazine]]|access-date = July 18, 2015|via = }}</ref>
** Citizens of Palau, Micronesia and the Marshall Islands may also join the US armed forces under the Compacts of Free Association, though some officer positions may be restricted.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2010/0505/Uncle-Sam-wants-Micronesians-for-US-military|title = Uncle Sam wants Micronesians for US military|last = Azios|first = Tony|date = May 5, 2010|work = |access-date = July 18, 2015|via = |newspaper = [[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref>
** Canadian-born Native Americans/First Nations may also join the US Armed Forces if they are of at least 50% blood quantum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Border Crossing Rights Under the Jay Treaty|url=http://ptla.org/border-crossing-rights-jay-treaty}}</ref>
** Additionally, under the [[Military accessions vital to national interest|Military Accessions Vital to National Interest]] (MAVNI) program, skilled foreigners such as translators may be recruited as needed, along with, as of September 2014 illegal immigrants with clean records and who have graduated high school if they were brought to the United States as children.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://news.vice.com/article/the-pentagon-will-allow-undocumented-immigrants-to-join-the-us-military|title = The Pentagon Will Allow Undocumented Immigrants to Join the US Military|last = Dyer|first = John|date = September 26, 2014|work = [[Vice News]]|access-date = July 18, 2015|via = }}</ref> As of December 2016, MAVNI is under review and closed indefinitely.
* {{flagcountry|United Arab Emirates}}
** There are people from other Arab or nearby Muslim countries, who have served in the UAE, mainly in non-uniformed positions. This was mainly after independence from the UK in 1971, when the UAE government was still evolving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/639766/uae-national-day-pakistan-helped-evolve-uae-armed-forces-says-consul-general/|title=UAE national day: Pakistan helped evolve UAE armed forces, says consul-general|work=The Express Tribune}}</ref> Prior to that, the UK stationed their own troops and equipment in the region (known as the [[Trucial States]]){{citation needed|date=May 2016}}

