The '''Médiathèque Musicale Mahler''' is a multimedia library with collections relating to music of the 19th and 20th centuries. The institution is located in an elegant private house near the [[Parc Monceau]] in Paris at 11 bis rue de Vézelay ([[8th arrondissement of Paris|8th arrondissement]]). It was founded in 1986 as the '''Bibliothèque Gustav Mahler''' by the French biographer of [[Gustav Mahler|Mahler]], musicologist [[Henry-Louis de La Grange]] (born 1924) and music critic, composer, and administrator [[Maurice Fleuret]] (1932&ndash;1990) in order to combine and make available to the public their extensive personal archives. The library's holdings have regularly been expanded and updated, and include original manuscript scores, letters, and other documents, and published scores, books, periodicals, press clippings, recordings (LPs, cassettes, and CDs), and other personal archives. The current president of the library, [[Pierre Bergé]] (born 1930), is a former director of the [[Théâtre de l'Athénée-Louis Jouvet]] and President of the [[Paris Opera]] (1988&ndash;1994) and succeeded La Grange as president of the library in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Home |publisher=Médiathèque Musicale Mahler website |url=http://www.mediathequemahler.org/en/ |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=Historique>{{Cite web |title=Historique|publisher=Médiathèque Musicale Mahler website |url=http://www.mediathequemahler.org/collections/historique/historique.html |accessdate=27 September 2010|language=fr}} </ref>
The association changed its name from '''Centre de Documentation Musicale-Bibliothèque Gustav Mahler''' to Médiathèque Musicale Mahler in 2002.<ref name=Historique/>
